{"cells": [{"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "147bf201", "metadata": {}, "source": ["# Overview of `unmap`\n", "\n", "This library aims to do 2 things:\n", "\n", "1. Guess the colourmap from a pseudocolour image, for those occasions when the colourmap is not known and not published along with the image.\n", "1. Recover ('unmap') the data from a pseudocolour image, essentially performing the reverse of the pseudocolour process.\n", "\n", "These 2 distinct tasks are illustrated below."]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 1, "id": "3091fc50", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"text/plain": ["<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x7eff456e9720>"]}, "execution_count": 1, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}, {"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["from gio import generate_random_surface\n", "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n", "import matplotlib.cm as cm\n", "\n", "# Make a random surface and normalize it to the range [0, 1].\n", "data = generate_random_surface(size=(32, 32), random_seed=42).values\n", "data = (data - data.min()) / (data.max() - data.min())\n", "\n", "# Take a look at it.\n", "plt.imshow(data, cmap='Greys_r')"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "a530d1fb", "metadata": {}, "source": ["Note: this is a greyscale image; it's the closest thing we can make to a 'pure' visualization of the data. The values in the data array correspond to a grey level from 0 (black) to 1 (white).\n", "\n", "If we were to look closely at the top-left corner, it's just a grid of numbers..."]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 2, "id": "d61174af", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n", "for i in range(5):\n", "    for j in range(5):\n", "        ax.text(i, j, f'{data[i, j]:0.2f}', ha='center')\n", "ax.imshow(data[:5, :5], vmin=0, vmax=1)\n", "ax.axis('off')\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "36c0451a", "metadata": {}, "source": ["Now we'll make an RGB image out of this 2D array. This involves using a look-up table of colours, called a **colourmap**, to transform each data value into an RGB colour, which is a 3-tuple of floats like (0.25, 0.33, 0.9). In doing so, we lose the data values themselves; they are now encoded as colours."]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 3, "id": "ef0d91fd", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"text/plain": ["<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x7eff453bca90>"]}, "execution_count": 3, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}, {"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["# Make a pseudocolored RGB image array.\n", "imarray = cm.turbo(data)\n", "\n", "# Display the RGB image.\n", "plt.imshow(imarray)"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "85730e4d", "metadata": {}, "source": ["If we know the colourmap and the original range of the data, then recovering data from this image is not too hard: we can do a reverse look-up of each colour in the image and replace it with the corresponding data value. This library, `unmap`, can handle this.\n", "\n", "On the other hand, without knowledge of the colourmap, or the range of values in the original array, it is hard to recover the original dataset from this image. But in some cases, `unmap` can help with this too."]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "de210c87", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Guess the colourmap\n", "\n", "We know that we used the `jet` colormap to create this image, but that information is not contained in the image. It's just a 3D NumPy array.\n", "\n", "Let's see if `unmap.guess_cmap_from_array()` can guess the colourmap we used:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 4, "id": "a41ba1a2", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/html": ["<div style=\"vertical-align: middle;\"><strong>recovered</strong> </div><div class=\"cmap\"><img alt=\"recovered colormap\" title=\"recovered\" style=\"border: 1px solid #555;\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></div><div style=\"vertical-align: middle; max-width: 514px; display: flex; justify-content: space-between;\"><div style=\"float: left;\"><div title=\"#30123bff\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 1em; height: 1em; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; border: 1px solid #555; background-color: #30123bff;\"></div> under</div><div style=\"margin: 0 auto; display: inline-block;\">bad <div title=\"#00000000\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 1em; height: 1em; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; border: 1px solid #555; background-color: #00000000;\"></div></div><div style=\"float: right;\">over <div title=\"#7b0402ff\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 1em; height: 1em; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; border: 1px solid #555; background-color: #7b0402ff;\"></div></div>"], "text/plain": ["<matplotlib.colors.LinearSegmentedColormap at 0x7eff4568ca00>"]}, "execution_count": 4, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}], "source": ["import unmap\n", "\n", "cmap = unmap.guess_cmap_from_array(imarray)\n", "cmap"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "0e982d01", "metadata": {}, "source": ["Phew!
